pulltitle: bad login failure page, fixes #827
pullsbody:
This solves the problem for Air Mozilla. I had a very convoluted, but valid, way of testing this. 
First I log in, then I go into a Django shell and decode the session data in the database, In it there's a `oidc_id_token_expiration` which is a timestamp. I changed that back to a low number, encode the session data and put it back into the database. That simulates that the user is still signed in but needs to refresh its ID token. But before letting the browser do that automatically, I type in `http://localhost:8000/oidc/callback/?error=anything` in the address bar and then every time I get the crazy redirect loop. But I actually had to intercept the successful callbacks too to simulate Auth0 being really unhappy. 

With this patch that problem went away and it was no longer possible to simulate the problem.
pull_repo_desc: AirMozilla is the video broadcasting site for the Mozilla project
pull_commit_message: bad login failure page, fixes #827

pulltitle: fixes bug 1265070 - improve transcoding wait message
pullsbody: This is what it looks like if it's **either** errored or the time left is a negative number: Users don't care if it errored or not. It's still "transcoding" as far as they're concerned. The event is still in the state of processing. This is what it looks like if it's got a positive number of seconds left: I tried to get fancy but it never really worked well. This is simple and a good start. It's much better than what we have already. The clever thing is that when the seconds slowly drop down more and more, when it hits 100% the status of the event updates (thanks to Vid.ly informing us with a webhook) and updates to the event trigger the websocket to refresh the page.
pull_repo_desc: AirMozilla is the video broadcasting site for the Mozilla project
pull_commit_message: fixes bug 1265070 - improve transcoding wait message

pull_commit_message:
Add a 1.25X playback rate option

YouTube supports this playback rate, and it seems like it works
much better than 1.5X when listening to someone speak, in that at
1.5X, what they are saying starts to get hard to understand in a
lot of cases.

pulltitle: Change update.py to match chief-james's expecations.
pullsbody:
chief-james expects update.py to unconditionally check out the ref that is passed. Previously, update_code would treat the parameter passed to it as a branch name to check out and update. This changes update_code to treat the parameter passed as a ref to get from the server, matching chief-james's expectations.

@peterbe r?
pull_repo_desc: AirMozilla is the video broadcasting site for the Mozilla project
pull_commit_message:
Change update.py to match chief-james's expecations.

chief-james expects update.py to unconditionally check out the ref that
is passed. Previously, update_code would treat the parameter passed to
it as a branch name to check out and update. This changes update_code to
treat the parameter passed as a ref to get from the server, matching
chief-james's expectations.

fixes bug 1197960

pulltitle: fixes bug 870015 - background reloading on event state change
pullsbody:
Hi @peterbe 

This is a pull request for the [bug](https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=870015) you suggested I look at previously such that if the event status for a live event changes to pending or from pending to archived it will reload the page. Thanks for the suggestion it certainly felt a little more challenging!

I look forward to hearing any feedback as I wasn't 100% sure on the best way to do this one - particularly with respect to how the javascript accesses the data it needs from the html page.

I would also like to add a test for the view but I have held off doing that for now as I am still figuring out how to do that.

thanks, Alex

pulltitle: fixes bug 1170727 - Removing Response class duplication in tests
pullsbody:
As Peter Bengtsson advised to do on [bugzilla](https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=1170727), I moved the Response class that was duplicated across multiple test classes into airmozilla.base.tests.testbase.

Response was implemented slightly differently in airmozilla/manage/tests/test_autocompleter vs the rest. The `json()` method returned `json.loads(self.content)` instead of simply `self.content` like the Response class in the other test classes did.

Therefore I subclassed Response from airmozilla.base.tests.testbase in test_autocompleter with the slightly different `json()` method and called it `JsonLoadingResponse` since it is loading the json instead of just returning the content of the response.

Please let me know if this is not the best way to do it or if there is any way it can be improved and I will happily revisit. Thank you
pull_repo_desc: AirMozilla is the video broadcasting site for the Mozilla project
pull_commit_message: fixes bug 1170727 - Removing Response class duplication in tests

pullsbody:
Bit of a work-in-progress, I suspect there may be some more templates to touch.

There may be a better way of doing this, but I've added a block for 'body_class' in the base template and any pages that should have a sidebar get the class 'with-sidebar'. pulltitle: Bug#1115451- Cache invalidation for deleting pictures
pullsbody:
When a picture is deleted the get_all_pictures key is removed from the cache but any event associated with the picture has the key as get_all_pictures+event.id in the cache. That's why the reference still persists. To rectify that, before rendering the page just check whether  the result from trying to get 'get_all_pictures' is the same as the result from the 'get_all_pictures+event.id' case. If it is, wonderful else something happened (this could be that the picture was deleted or a new picture was added or both happened, one after the other. In this case always go to the db and reset the cache values).

The test is only for the case mentioned in the bug.
pull_repo_desc: AirMozilla is the video broadcasting site for the Mozilla project

pulltitle: trash
pullsbody:
Although confirm-delete.js should have done the task of popping out a confirmation dialogue box, since the <tr> tag with the attribute 'ng-repeat' makes jQuery to act on angularjs's product (elements inside <td>), it won't work[1].

We can also use ng-click to do the same.

[1] = https://docs.angularjs.org/misc/faq (under 'DOM Manipulation')

Update tags.html

Although confirm-delete.js should have done the task of popping out a confirmation dialogue box, since the <tr> tag with the attribute 'ng-repeat' makes jQuery to act on angularjs's product (elements inside <td>), it won't work[1].

We can also use ng-click to do the same.

[1] = https://docs.angularjs.org/misc/faq (under 'DOM Manipulation')
